\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Commentary
\emph default
.
 More 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

obvious, but the game is that we have to do it from the axioms.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 A helpful margin note on p.
 12 points out that the only part of the definition of a vector space that
 connects scalar multiplication and the additive identity is the distributive
 property.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I was struggling on how to proceed here (either directly or taking the contrapos
itive).
 A hint from Claude asks what property 
\begin_inset Formula $a\ne0$
\end_inset

 has in a field that it wouldn't in a ring, and then I see it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Proof
\emph default
.
 Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $av=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the case 
\begin_inset Formula $a\ne0$
\end_inset

.
 Then we can divide by 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $av=0$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{a}{a}v=\frac{0}{a}$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $1v=0$
\end_inset

 implies 
\begin_inset Formula $v=0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $a=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $v=0$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is true because the second disjunct is true.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now consider the case 
\begin_inset Formula $a=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $a=0$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $v=0$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is true because the first disjunct is true.
