\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
6
\series default
.
 
\emph on
Proposition
\emph default
.
 There exists a nonempty subset of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 that is closed under addition and taking additive inverses but is not a
 subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Commentary
\emph default
.
 It didn't initially seem to me like this should exist.
 My intuitive example for a linear-algebraically 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

nice
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 subset that isn't a linear subspace is an affine subspace that doesn't
 contain zero, but closure under addition and inverses says that if 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in U$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $v+(-v)=0\in U$
\end_inset

.
 How else could something so 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

nice
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (closure under addition and inverses) fail to be a subspace?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Proof
\emph default
.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is not a subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

, because it's not closed under scalar multiplication by elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
7
\series default
.
 
\emph on
Proposition
\emph default
.
 There exists a nonempty subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is closed under scalar multiplication but is not a subspace of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Proof
\emph default
.
 Consider the union of two unequal subspaces: say 
\begin_inset Formula $X:=\{\left[\begin{array}{c}
a\\
0
\end{array}\right]:a\in\mathbb{R}\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y:=\{\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
a
\end{array}\right]:a\in\mathbb{R}\}$
\end_inset

.
 For any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

 and any 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $cx\in X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $cy\in Y$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $X\cup Y$
\end_inset

 is not a subspace because it's not closed under addition.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
8
\series default
.
 
\emph on
Theorem
\emph default
.
 The intersection of subspaces is a subspace.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Proof
\emph default
.
 Suppose that 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}$
\end_inset

 are subspaces of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

 is just an index into some index set; you know what I mean.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Additive identity.) For all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in V_{i}$
\end_inset

 (because each 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a subspace), so 
\begin_inset Formula $0\in\bigcap_{i}V_{i}$
\end_inset

, too.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\checkmark$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Additive closure.) If 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v\in\bigcap_{i}V_{i}$
\end_inset

, then for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $u,v\in V_{i}$
\end_inset

, so for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $u+v\in V_{i}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $u+v\in\bigcap_{i}V_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\checkmark$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(Scalar multiplication closure.) If for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in I$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V_{i}$
\end_inset

, then for call 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in\mathbb{F}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $cv\in V_{i}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $cv\in\bigcap_{i}V_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\checkmark$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
9
\series default
.
 
\emph on
Theorem
\emph default
.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}$
\end_inset

 are subspaces of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\cup U_{2}$
\end_inset

 is a subspace iff 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\subseteq U_{2}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}\subseteq U_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Commentary
\emph default
.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\Leftarrow$
\end_inset

 direction is easy.
 In the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

 direction, what is the intuitive reason that non-nested subspaces aren't
 a subspace? Imagine two lines through the origin: the sum of a non-origin
 vector from each line isn't on either line, so we don't have additive closure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Proof
\emph default
.
 (
\begin_inset Formula $\Leftarrow$
\end_inset

) Suppose without loss of generality that 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\subseteq U_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\cup U_{2}$
\end_inset

 is a subspace because 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\cup U_{2}=U_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}$
\end_inset

 is a subspace.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(
\begin_inset Formula $\Rightarrow$
\end_inset

) Taking the contrapositive, we want to show that if 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\not\subseteq U_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}\not\subseteq U_{1}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\cup U_{2}$
\end_inset

 is not a subspace.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U_{1}\backslash U_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in U_{2}\backslash U_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $x+y\notin U_{1}\cup U_{2}$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in U_{1}\cup U_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in U_{1}\cup U_{2}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}\cup U_{2}$
\end_inset

 is not closed under addition.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
10
\series default
.
 
\emph on
Proposition
\emph default
.
 The sum of a subspace with itself is that subspace: 
\begin_inset Formula $U+U=U$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Proof
\emph default
.
 
\begin_inset Formula $U+U:=\{u_{1}+u_{2}:u_{1},u_{2}\in U\}$
\end_inset

 by definition.
 Any 
\begin_inset Formula $u\in U$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula $u+0$
\end_inset

—effectively taking 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}:=0$
\end_inset

 in the set-builder definition.
 But taking 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}\ne0$
\end_inset

 doesn't add any new points, because vector spaces are closed under addition.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
11
\series default
.
 
\emph on
Theorem
\emph default
.
 Addition of subspaces is commutative: 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}+U_{2}=U_{2}+U_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Proof.

\emph default
 From the commutativity of addition: 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}+U_{2}:=\{u_{1}+u_{2}:u_{1}\in U_{1},u_{2}\in U_{2}\}=\{u_{2}+u_{1}:u_{1}\in U_{1},u_{2}\in U_{2}\}=U_{2}+U_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Theorem
\emph default
.
 Addition of subspaces is associative: 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{1}+U_{2})+U_{3}=U_{1}+(U_{2}+U_{3})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Proof
\emph default
.
 From the associativity of addition: 
\begin_inset Formula $(U_{1}+U_{2})+U_{3}:=\{u_{12}+u_{3}:u_{12}\in\{u_{1}+u_{2}:u_{1}\in U_{1},u_{2}\in U_{2}\},u_{3}\in U_{3}\}=\{(u_{1}+u_{2})+u_{3}:u_{1}\in U_{1},u_{2}\in U_{2},u_{3}\in U_{3}\}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $=\{u_{1}+(u_{2}+u_{3}):u_{1}\in U_{1},u_{2}\in U_{2},u_{3}\in U_{3}\}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
12
\series default
.
 
\emph on
Proposition
\emph default
.
 The trivial subspace is an additive identity for subspace addition.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Proof
\emph default
.
 
\begin_inset Formula $0+U:=\{0+u:u\in U\}=\{u:u\in U\}=U$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Proposition
\emph default
.
 Only the trivial subspace has an additive inverse.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Proof
\emph default
.
 Suppose not.
 Then there exists a nontrivial subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 such that there exists a nontrivial subspace 
\begin_inset Formula $-U$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $U+(-U)=0$
\end_inset

.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $U+(-U):=\{u_{+}+u_{-}:u_{+}\in U,u_{-}\in-U\}$
\end_inset

.
 Zero belongs to every subspace, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\{u_{+}+0:u_{+}\in U\}\subseteq U+(-U)$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq U+(-U)$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subseteq0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $U=0$
\end_inset

, but 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 was supposed to be nontrivial.
 Contradiction!
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

