.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\emph on
Proof
\emph default
 
\emph on
attempt
\emph default
.
 By the definition of a direct sum, 
\begin_inset Formula $V=U_{1}\oplus W$
\end_inset

 means that an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 can be written 
\emph on
uniquely
\emph default
 as a sum of elements from 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

, and similarly for 
\begin_inset Formula $U_{2}\oplus W$
\end_inset

.
 Consider an arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in V$
\end_inset

.
 Then there exists a unique 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}\in U_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{2}\in U_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{1},w_{2}\in W$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $v=u_{1}+w_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v=u_{2}+w_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 If we knew that 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{1}=w_{2}$
\end_inset

, we would quickly be done, but do we know that?
